# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: american-expeditionary-force-north-russia
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1958-c-130-shootdown-incident] The **1958 C-130 shootdown incident** was the shooting down of an American Lockheed C-130A-II-LM reconnaissance aircraft which entered Soviet airspace during a mission in the region of Armenian SSR.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1958-c-130-shootdown-incident] On September 2, 1958, a Lockheed C-130A-II-LM (s/n 56-0528), from the 7406th Support Squadron, departed Incirlik Airbase in Turkey on a reconnaissance mission along the Turkish-Soviet border.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1958-c-130-shootdown-incident] It was to fly a course parallel to the frontier, but not approach the border closer than 100 miles (160 km).
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1958-c-130-shootdown-incident] The crew reported passing over Trabzon in Turkey at 25,500 feet (7,800 m) and then acknowledged a weather report from Trabzon, but that was the last communication received from the flight.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1958-c-130-shootdown-incident] It was later intercepted and shot down by four Soviet MiG-17s 34 mi (55 km; 30 nmi) north-west of Yerevan.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1958-c-130-shootdown-incident] The six flight crew were confirmed dead when their remains were repatriated to the United States, but the 11 intelligence-gathering personnel on board have never been acknowledged by Soviet / Russian authorities.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1958-c-130-shootdown-incident] In 1993, after the fall of the Soviet Union, a US excavation team working in newly-independent Armenia found hundreds of skeletal fragments; two remains were identified.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1958-c-130-shootdown-incident] A group burial of the 17 crew remains was held at Arlington National Cemetery.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1958-c-130-shootdown-incident] When NSA cryptologists William Hamilton Martin and Bernon F.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1958-c-130-shootdown-incident] Mitchell defected to the Soviet Union in 1960, they listed the C-130 flight as one of their reasons.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1958-c-130-shootdown-incident] They contended that it was designed to gain an understanding of Soviet defenses, and that it therefore possibly represented an American interest in attacking the Soviets rather than defending against them.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1958-c-130-shootdown-incident] James Bamford, an investigative journalist and author, agreed that their assertions had merit.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1958-c-130-shootdown-incident] In 1993, Armenian sculptor Martin Kakosian unveiled a khachkar, a traditional Armenian cross stone, at the site of the aircraft's crash in the village of Nerkin Sasnashen.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1958-c-130-shootdown-incident] Kakosian had witnessed the crash as a college student on a field trip in 1958.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1958-c-130-shootdown-incident] This khachkar later fell over and cracked, and a joint US-Armenian memorial was built to commemorate the site.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1958-c-130-shootdown-incident] In 2011, the US Army Office of Defense Cooperation renovated the village kindergarten in appreciation of the villagers' commemoration of the downed airmen.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1958-c-130-shootdown-incident] The shootdown features in the British documentary "Spies in the Sky" (October 22, 1994), an edition in the BBC's *Timewatch'* series.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1958-c-130-shootdown-incident] It includes footage of the 1993 unveiling of the Nerkin Sasnashen memorial, attended by the sister of one of the USAF crewmen.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-rb-47-shootdown-incident] On 1 July 1960, a United States RB-47H reconnaissance plane was shot down by the Soviet Air Defence Forces while performing signals intelligence in the Barents Sea, near the Kola Peninsula, off the Arctic coast of the Soviet Union.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-rb-47-shootdown-incident] The shootdown occurred exactly two months after the far better known U-2 shootdown involving Francis Gary Powers, and added to the tensions created by that incident.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-rb-47-shootdown-incident] The plane was part of the 55th Strategic Reconnaissance Wing and took off from RAF Brize Norton airbase in the United Kingdom.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-rb-47-shootdown-incident] It was shot down by Soviet pilot Vasily Polyakov in a MiG-19.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-rb-47-shootdown-incident] The US position was that the plane was in international waters, and this was later corroborated by information provided by spy Oleg Penkovsky.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-rb-47-shootdown-incident] Three of the crewmen (reconnaissance officers Capt.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-rb-47-shootdown-incident] Eugene Posa) were missing in action, and the remains of one other (aircraft commander Maj.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-rb-47-shootdown-incident] The two survivors, navigator Captain John R.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-rb-47-shootdown-incident] McKone and co-pilot Captain Freeman "Bruce" Olmstead, were picked up by Soviet fishing trawlers and held in Lubyanka prison in Moscow until immediately after the inauguration of newly elected US President John F.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-rb-47-shootdown-incident] Kennedy on 20 January 1961, when they were released by Soviet leader Nikita Khrushchev as a goodwill gesture.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-rb-47-shootdown-incident] McKone and Olmstead appeared on the cover of the 3 February 1961 issue of *Time* magazine.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-rb-47-shootdown-incident] In his news conference on 21 April 1961, Kennedy was asked if the dropping of charges against an accused Soviet spy was in exchange for the release of the RB-47 aviators.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-rb-47-shootdown-incident] As a result of their involvement in the incident, Olmstead and McKone received POW medals in 1996 and Silver Star medals in 2004, as well as the Distinguished Flying Cross.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] On 1 May 1960, a United States U-2 spy plane, having taken off from Peshawar in Pakistan, was shot down by the Soviet Air Defence Forces in Sverdlovsk, Russia.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] It was conducting photographic aerial reconnaissance inside Soviet territory while being flown by American pilot Francis Gary Powers, as it was hit by a surface-to-air missile.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] Powers parachuted to the ground and was captured.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] The incident occurred during the tenures of American president Dwight D.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] Eisenhower and Soviet leader Nikita Khrushchev, around two weeks before the scheduled opening of an east–west summit in Paris, France.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] Khrushchev and Eisenhower had met face-to-face at Camp David in Maryland in September 1959, and the seeming thaw in US-Soviet relations had raised hopes globally for a peaceful resolution to the Cold War.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] The U-2 incident shattered the amiable "Spirit of Camp David" that had prevailed for eight months, prompting the cancellation of the summit in Paris and embarrassing the US on the international stage.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] The Pakistani government issued a formal apology to the Soviet Union for its role in the mission.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] After his capture, Powers was convicted of espionage and sentenced to three years of imprisonment plus seven years of hard labour; he was released two years later, in February 1962, in a prisoner exchange for Soviet intelligence officer Rudolf Abel.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] Eisenhower requested permission from the Pakistani prime minister Feroze Khan Noon for the US to establish a secret intelligence facility in Pakistan and for the U-2 spy plane to fly from Pakistan.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] The U-2 flew at altitudes that could not be reached by Soviet fighter jets of the era; it was believed to be beyond the reach of Soviet missiles as well.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] A facility established in Badaber (Peshawar Air Station), 16 kilometres (9.9 mi) from Peshawar, was a cover for a major communications intercept operation run by the United States National Security Agency (NSA).
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] Badaber was an excellent location because of its proximity to Soviet central Asia.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] This enabled the monitoring of missile test sites, key infrastructure and communications.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] The U-2 "spy-in-the-sky" was allowed to use the Pakistan Air Force section of Peshawar Airport to gain vital photo intelligence in an era before satellite observation.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] Eisenhower did not want to fly American U-2 pilots over the Soviet Union.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] He believed that if one of these pilots were to be shot down or captured, the flight could be seen as an act of aggression that might spark open conflict.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] Someone suggested using British pilots from the Royal Air Force fly these missions instead of US Central Intelligence Agency (CIA) pilots, which would allow Eisenhower to deny US involvement.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] The British government consented to the proposal under the codename Project Oldster.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] After the success of the first two British pilots and because of desire to determine the number of Soviet intercontinental ballistic missiles more accurately, Eisenhower allowed the flying of two more missions before the Four Power Paris Summit, scheduled for 16 May.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] The final two missions before the summit were to be flown by American pilots.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] The aircraft was detected by the Soviet Air Defense Forces when it had flown more than 250 kilometres (155 mi) over the Soviet national boundary; it avoided attempts at interception by a MiG-19 and a Su-9.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] The U-2 left Soviet air space and landed at an Iranian airstrip at Zahedan, completing an extraordinarily dangerous but productive intelligence operation.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] The next flight of the U-2 spy plane from Peshawar airport was planned for late April.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] Dubbed "Grand Slam", the flight was to leave the base in Peshawar and overfly the Soviet Union.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] The photographic targets included the Soviet's ICBM launch pads: two at Baikonur Cosmodrome and four at Plesetsk Cosmodrome.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] Another target was Chelyabinsk-65 (today, Mayak), an important industrial center of plutonium processing.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] The flight would end with a landing at Bodø in Norway.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] On 28 April 1960, a US Lockheed U-2C spy plane, Article 358, was ferried from Incirlik Air Base in Turkey to the US base at Peshawar airport by pilot Glen Dunaway.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] Fuel for the aircraft had been ferried to Peshawar the previous day in a US Air Force C-124 transport.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] An Air Force C-130 followed, carrying the ground crew, mission pilot Captain Francis Powers, and backup pilot Bob Ericson.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] On the morning of 29 April, the crew in Badaber was informed that the mission had been delayed by one day.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] As a result, Ericson flew Article 358 back to Incirlik and John Shinn ferried another U-2C, Article 360 56–6693, from Incirlik to Peshawar.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] On 30 April, the mission was delayed one day further because of bad weather over the Soviet Union.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] The weather improved and on 1 May, 15 days before the scheduled opening of the east–west summit conference in Paris, Powers took off for Grand Slam in Article 360.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] The U-2 flight was expected, and all units of the Soviet Air Defence Forces in the Central Asia, Kazakhstan, Siberia, Ural, and later in the USSR European Region and Extreme North, were placed on red alert.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] Soon after the aircraft was detected, Lieutenant General of the Air Force Yevgeniy Savitskiy ordered the air-unit commanders "to attack the violator by all alert flights located in the area of foreign plane's course, and to ram if necessary".
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] Because of the U-2's extreme altitude, Soviet attempts to intercept the aircraft using fighter aircraft failed.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] The U-2's course was out of range of several of the nearest SAM sites, and one SAM site failed to engage the aircraft since it was not on duty that day.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] Powers' account of the flight shows that one of the last targets he overflew was the Chelyabinsk-65 plutonium production facility.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] His U-2 was shot down near Kosulino, Ural Region, by the first of three S-75 Dvina surface-to-air missiles fired by a battery commanded by Mikhail Voronov.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] The S-75 site had been supposedly identified previously by the CIA, using photos taken during Vice President Richard Nixon's visit to Sverdlovsk the previous summer.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] Powers bailed out but neglected to disconnect his oxygen hose and struggled with it until it broke, enabling him to separate from the aircraft.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] After parachuting safely onto Soviet soil, Powers was quickly captured.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] Powers carried a modified silver dollar which contained a lethal, shellfish-derived saxitoxin-tipped needle, but he did not use it.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] The SAM command center was unaware for more than 30 minutes that the aircraft was destroyed.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] One of the Soviet MiG-19 fighters pursuing Powers was also destroyed in the missile salvo, and the pilot, Sergei Safronov, was killed.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] The MiGs' IFF transponders were not yet switched to the new May codes because of the 1 May holiday.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] US officials initially believed that Powers had died and his plane was destroyed.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] They decided to try a cover-up, which failed, enabling Nikita Khrushchev to embarrass President Eisenhower and his administration.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] On 5 May, four days after Powers' disappearance, NASA issued a detailed press release noting that an aircraft had "gone missing" north of Turkey.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] The press release speculated that the pilot might have fallen unconscious while the autopilot was still engaged, even falsely claiming that "the pilot reported over the emergency frequency that he was experiencing oxygen difficulties".
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] To bolster this, a U-2 was quickly painted in NASA colors and shown to the media.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] That same day, the Senate made its first comments on the U-2 incident and began a domestic political controversy for Eisenhower.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] Mike Mansfield, the Senate Majority Whip, stated, "First reports indicate that the President had no knowledge of the plane incident.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] When Khrushchev heard about America's NASA cover story, he developed a political trap for Eisenhower.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] He announced that a spy plane had been shot down in Soviet territory, but he did not reveal that the pilot of this aircraft had been found and that he was alive.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] This led US officials to believe they could continue with their cover story that the crashed U-2 was a weather research aircraft.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] Building on the lie that the pilot had experienced oxygen difficulties while flying over Turkey, they declared that the pilot may have passed out and the aircraft continued on autopilot into Soviet airspace.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] To bolster the story, they grounded all U-2 aircraft for inspection of oxygen systems.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] To buttress his claims, Khrushchev released photos of U-2 systems.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] Khrushchev attempted to allow Eisenhower to save face, and possibly to salvage the peace summit to some degree, by laying the blame not on Eisenhower himself, but on Director of Central Intelligence Allen Dulles and the CIA.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] Khrushchev said that anyone wishing to understand the U-2's mission should "seek a reply from Allen Dulles, at whose instructions the American aircraft flew over the Soviet Union".
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] On 9 May, the Soviet premier told US ambassador Thompson that he "could not help but suspect that someone had launched this operation with the deliberate intent of spoiling the summit meeting".
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] Thompson also wrote in his diplomatic cable that Khrushchev suspected it was Allen Dulles, and that Khrushchev had heard about Senator Mansfield's remarks that Eisenhower did not control his own administration.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] Upon receiving this cable, Eisenhower, who frequently was very animated, was quiet and depressed.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] The only words he said to his secretary were, "I would like to resign." Meanwhile, the domestic pressure continued to mount.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] Eisenhower then accepted Dulles's argument that the congressional leadership needed to be briefed on the U-2 missions from the last four years.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] Dulles told the legislature that all U-2 flights were used for aerial espionage and had been flown pursuant to "presidential directives".
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] Still, Dulles played down Eisenhower's direct role in approving every previous U-2 flight.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] The next day, on 10 May, House Appropriations Chair Clarence Cannon, not President Eisenhower, revealed the true nature of the U-2 mission.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] He told an open session of the House of Representatives that the U-2 was a CIA aircraft engaged in aerial espionage over the Soviet Union.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] At the end of Cannon's speech, Democrats and Republicans uncharacteristically rose to their feet to applaud.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] Still, Eisenhower faced criticism in the press for not controlling his own administration, as Cannon's speech only said the mission was "under the aegis of" the president, not "directed by".
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] Press reports were creating a belief in the public that Eisenhower had lost control, which Eisenhower would not let stand.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] Knowing that he was jeopardizing the Paris Peace Summit, Eisenhower decided to reveal the aerial espionage program and his direct role in it, an unprecedented move for a US president.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] Eisenhower closed passionately by reacting to the Soviet claim that the US acted provocatively and said: "They had better look at their own [espionage] record." As he finished, he told reporters he was still going to the Paris Peace Summit.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] Such reasoning, while constrained, is hardly unusual.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] A large part of the wreck as well as many items from Powers' survival pack are on display at the Central Armed Forces Museum in Moscow.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] A small piece of the U-2 was returned to the United States and is on display at the National Cryptologic Museum.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] The Summit was attended by Eisenhower, Khrushchev, French President Charles de Gaulle, and British Prime Minister Harold Macmillan.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] It was the first conference to be attended by both Soviet and western leaders in five years.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] However, prospects for constructive dialogue were dashed by the explosive controversy surrounding the U-2 flight over Soviet territory.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] Although the Four Powers Summit was the first meeting between western and Soviet leaders in five years when it was held, the mood was optimistic that there could be an easing of tensions between the Soviet Union and the United States.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] In an effort to present a less hostile, more cordial Soviet Union, Khrushchev publicly advocated a policy of "peaceful coexistence with the United States".
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] The May Day celebrations on 1 May of that year were marked by this newfound cooperative spirit.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] Absent were the militarized symbols of previous parades, such as artillery and armor.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] Instead, there were children, white doves, and athletes.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] But the reaction of the Soviet government to the spy plane incident and the response from the United States doomed any potential meaningful peace agreement.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] In the days directly leading up to the conference, tensions increased dramatically between the United States and the Soviet Union over the U-2 incident.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] At this point in the negotiations, the hardliners of the Soviet government were applying heavy pressure to Khrushchev.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] At this time east and west were divided about how to move forward in Berlin, and the American press characterized Khrushchev's decision to emphasize the U-2 incident at the summit as an attempt to gain leverage on this issue.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] The summit itself did not last long, with talks only beginning on 15 May and ending on 16 May.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] Both Eisenhower and Khrushchev gave statements on the 16th.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] Khrushchev blasted the United States on the U-2 incident.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] He pointed out that the policy of secret spying was one of mistrust and that the incident had doomed the summit before it even began.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] He expected the United States and Eisenhower to condemn the spying and pledge to end further reconnaissance missions.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] At the summit, after Khrushchev had blown Eisenhower's cover, Eisenhower did not deny that the aircraft had been spying on Soviet military installations but contended that the action was not aggressive but defensive.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] He argued that the current state of international relations was not one in which peaceful coexistence was an already established fact.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] The policy of the United States towards the Soviet Union at that time was defensive and cautionary.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] Eisenhower also made the point that dialogue at the Four Powers Summit was the type of international negotiation that could lead to a relationship between the United States and the Soviet Union where there would be no need to spy on each other.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] Eisenhower also laid out a plan for an international agreement that authorized the UN to "inspect" any nations willing to submit to its authority for signs of increased militarization and aggressive action.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] He stated that the United States would be more than willing to submit to such an inspection by the UN and that he hoped to circumvent the spying controversy with this alternative international surveillance agreement.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] The meeting during which both parties made their statements lasted just over three hours.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] During this time Khrushchev rescinded an invitation he had earlier given to Eisenhower to visit the Soviet Union.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] According to American broadcast journalist Walter Cronkite, Khrushchev would go on to say that this incident was the beginning of his decline in power as party chairman, perhaps because he seemed unable to negotiate the international arena and the communist hardliners at home.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] The collapse of the summit also saw an increased tension between the Soviets and the Americans in the years to come.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] After this debacle, the arms race accelerated and any considerations for negotiations were dashed for the immediate future.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] As a result of the spy plane incident and the attempted cover-up, the Four Power Paris Summit was not completed.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] At the beginning of the talks on 16 May, there was still hope that the two sides could come together even after the events that took place earlier in May, but Eisenhower refused to apologize and Khrushchev left the summit one day after it had begun.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] Even though Eisenhower refused to apologize, he did admit that the flights were "suspended and would not resume".
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] Some public opinion was that Khrushchev had overreacted to the event in an attempt to strengthen his own position, and for that, he was the one to blame for the collapse of the Four Power Paris Summit.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] Before the U-2 incident Khrushchev and Eisenhower had been getting along well and the summit was going to be an opportunity for the two sides to come together.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] Also, Eisenhower had been looking forward to a visit to the Soviet Union and was very upset when his invitation was retracted.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] The two sides were going to discuss topics such as nuclear arms reduction and also how to deal with increasing tensions surrounding Berlin.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] According to Eisenhower, had it not been for the U-2 incident, the summit and his visit to the Soviet Union could have greatly helped Soviet and American relations.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] The Soviet Union convened a meeting of the United Nations Security Council on 23 May to tell their side of the story.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] The incident also reverberated around the world.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] For example, in Japan, the incident contributed to the growth of the ongoing Anpo protests against the US-Japan Security Treaty (known as "Anpo" in Japanese) which allowed the United States to maintain military bases on Japanese soil.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] The Japanese government was forced to admit that U-2 planes were also based at US bases in Japan, which meant that Japan might be subject to attack should a war break out between the United States and the Soviet Union.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] Accordingly, when the U-2 revelations came to light, Japanese protesters felt added urgency in their drive to eliminate the treaty and rid Japan of US military bases.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] The U-2 incident severely compromised Pakistan's security and dented relations with the United States.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] After the incident, Nikita Khrushchev threatened to drop a nuclear bomb on Peshawar, thus warning Pakistan that it had become a target of Soviet nuclear forces.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] General Khalid Mahmud Arif of the Pakistan Army stated that "Pakistan felt deceived because the US had kept her in the dark about such clandestine spy operations launched from Pakistan's territory", although Pakistan's president Muhammad Ayub Khan may have known about the operations.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] Khan visited the USSR in 1965 and apologized for the incident.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] When Khan invited Soviet foreign minister Andrei Gromyko to visit Pakistan, pointing out he'd never visited the country, the latter sarcastically replied "I always keep ahead of the U-2".
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] The communications wing at Badaber was formally closed down on 7 January 1970.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] Further, the Senate Foreign Relations Committee held a lengthy inquiry into the U-2 incident.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] In the Norwegian Armed Forces, the U-2 incident caused "dirty laundry to be aired", but no blame was assigned; as of 2022, the archives from 1960 of Norwegian Intelligence Service have not been declassified.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] Upon his capture, Gary Powers told his Soviet captors what his mission had been and why he had been in Soviet airspace.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] He did this in accordance with orders that he had received before he went on his mission.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] Powers pleaded guilty and was convicted of espionage on 19 August and sentenced to three years imprisonment and seven years of hard labor.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] He served one year and nine months of the sentence before being exchanged for Rudolf Abel on 10 February 1962.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] The exchange occurred on the Glienicke Bridge connecting Potsdam, East Germany, to West Berlin.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] The incident showed that even high-altitude aircraft were vulnerable to Soviet surface-to-air missiles.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] As a result, the United States began emphasizing high-speed, low-level flights for its previously high altitude B-47, B-52 and B-58 bombers, and began developing the supersonic F-111, which would include an FB-111A variant for the Strategic Air Command.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] The Corona spy satellite project was accelerated.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] The CIA also accelerated the development of the Lockheed A-12 OXCART supersonic spyplane that first flew in 1962 and later began developing the Lockheed D-21 unmanned drone.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] As a result of the capture, the Russians reverse-engineered the U-2 and ended up producing the Beriev S-13, but development was cancelled after Powers was released.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] The original consensus about the cause of the U-2 incident was that the spy plane had been shot down by one of a salvo of 14 Soviet S-75 missiles.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] This story was originated by Oleg Penkovsky, a GRU agent who spied for MI6.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] One more recent reading of the NSA's story is that they mistakenly tracked the descent of a MiG-19 piloted by Sr.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] In 1996, Soviet pilot Captain Igor Mentyukov claimed that, at 19,800 metres (65,000 ft) altitude, under orders to ram the intruder, he had caught the U-2 in the slipstream of his unarmed Sukhoi Su-9, causing the U-2 to flip over and break its wings.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] The salvo of missiles had indeed scored a hit, downing a pursuing MiG-19, not the U-2.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] Mentyukov said that if a missile had hit the U-2, its pilot would not have lived.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] Though the normal Su-9 service ceiling was 16,800 metres (55,000 ft), Mentyukov's aircraft had been modified to achieve higher altitudes, having its weapons removed.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] With no weapons, the only attack option open to him was aerial ramming.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] Mentyukov asserted that Soviet generals concealed these facts to avoid challenging Nikita Khrushchev's faith in the efficiency of Soviet air defenses.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] In 1981, Selmer Nilsen, a Norwegian convicted for spying for the Soviet Union, claimed in his book 'I Was a Russian Spy' that Powers's U-2 had actually been sabotaged.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] He alleged that a bomb had been placed in the tail of the aircraft by two Soviet spies disguised as mechanics at a Turkish airfield.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] He claimed to have been told this by Soviet officials shortly after the incident.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] This may have been a contemporary 1962 theory also.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] Ian Fleming, writing his 1963 James Bond novel, *On Her Majesty's Secret Service*, had M mention to Bond during a briefing that "a plastic explosives expert was working for the KGB in Turkey.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] Fletcher Prouty was an Air Force officer who coordinated covert actions between the Joint Chiefs of Staff and the Central Intelligence Agency.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] In the 1990s, he gave an interview suggesting the incident was an elaborate disinformation operation with a secondary political goal of sabotaging peace talks.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] Prouty noted the U-2 did not carry the advanced camera, that the U-2 had previously crashed and had been rebuilt by Lockheed to non-standard specifications, and the hydrogen tank had only been half-filled, meaning it would have run out of fuel over the Soviet Union.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] The effect of such an operation would be to mislead the Soviet Union about the aircraft's capabilities such as camera resolution.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] In 2015, the Steven Spielberg feature film *Bridge of Spies* was released, which dramatized James B.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] Donovan (Tom Hanks)'s negotiations for Powers's release, but took certain liberties with what really happened.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] For instance, Powers is shown being tortured by the Soviets, when in reality he was treated well by his captors and spent much of his time doing handicrafts.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1960-u-2-incident] In January 2016, the BBC magazine produced photographs from the time and an interview with Powers's son.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] The event came at a historically difficult time in relations between West Germany and East Germany.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] Only a month before, the Berlin Wall had been built, which completely cut off West Berlin from surrounding East Germany and from East Berlin.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] It also came three days before the West German federal election, held on 17 September 1961.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] There were 38 violations of West Germany's air space by Soviet aircraft in a period of just four weeks between August and September 1961.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] Some of the violations were deliberate, to determine the opposite side's reaction, while others were by mistake, caused by the difficulty in determining the border line from the air.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] Between the end of the Second World War and the German reunification, West German planes were not permitted to fly to West Berlin, regardless of whether they were civilian or military aircraft.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] The three existing air corridors to the city were only open to planes from the three wartime Western Allies: the United States, France and the United Kingdom.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] On 14 September 1961, under the code name *Checkmate*, the NATO high command mobilised the air forces of France, Belgium, the Netherlands, Denmark, and West Germany for the purpose of an exercise.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] As part of this exercise, the *Jagdbomber*s of *Jagdbombergeschwader (JaBoG) 32*, based at Lechfeld Air Base, south of Augsburg, were to fly a triangular route from Würzburg to Laon and then to Memmingen.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] Two F-84 fighter-bombers, flown by Feldwebel Peter Pfefferkorn and Stabsunteroffizier Hans Eberl, lost their course in the process of flying this route, with the compass on Pfefferkorn's plane misreading by between 40 and 60 degrees.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] Additionally, a strong westerly wind was greater in strength than had been forecasted.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] On their way from Würzburg to Laon, the two pilots had become so disoriented that they mistook Liège in Belgium for Reims in France.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] Shortly after, the pair were picked up by NATO radar stations near Warburg, in southern Westphalia, heading east, in the direction of Königs Wusterhausen, south of Berlin.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] The two pilots missed a radio call from the radar stations advising them to turn around because they were talking to each other, trying to establish their location.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] It was only when reaching a position north of Leipzig, deep within East German air space, that Pfefferkorn sent a Mayday signal, which was picked up, to their surprise, by the French-controlled airport at Tegel in West Berlin, which gave them permission to land.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] The planes had initially not been noticed by the radar operator at the Berlin Tempelhof Airport because he was concentrating on an incoming Pan Am Douglas DC-6.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] By the time they were noticed, the pair were being unsuccessfully chased by a large number of Soviet fighter aircraft.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] An airman in the Berlin Air Route Traffic Control Center ordered the two pilots not to turn around and face the pursuing fighter planes but instead to head for the Tegel airport as it had a longer runway than Tempelhof and was more suitable for jets.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] Because of the actions of this airman and the heavy cloud cover, which the two pilots used to conceal themselves, Pfefferkorn and Eberl escaped the pursuing Soviet aircraft and successfully landed their planes without further incident at Tegel.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] Immediately after the two aircraft landed, the French authorities at Tegel airport explained to the Soviet authorities in East Berlin that, because of technical difficulties, an emergency landing of the two planes had been absolutely necessary.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] The then-West German Minister of Defence, Franz-Josef Strauß, apologised to the Soviet ambassador in Bonn for the incident, sending his secretary of state, Volkmar Hopf.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] The government of the Soviet Union remained silent for a number of days with regards to the incident, before officially protesting against the West German "provocation" and threatening to shoot down any aircraft involved if the incident was repeated.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] The Soviet air command in East Germany was less than impressed with the 'unpunished' flight of two Western fighter planes through their airspace.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] However, it chose to blame bad weather for the incident rather than the failure of its ground control to guide the Soviet fighter planes on to the West German ones.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] When Kammhuber announced this order at Lechfeld the following day, it was dubbed *Bier Order 61* (*Beer Order 61*) because it was formulated late at night over drinks between Kammhuber and Strauß.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] Barth, commander of *JaBoG 32*, was not questioned with regard to the incident, and was not allowed to speak during Kammhuber's visit.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] Instead, Generalleutnant Martin Harlinghausen, Barth's superior officer, who had once, in 1944, stood up to Hermann Göring, spoke for Barth and demanded a proper investigation.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] Two weeks later, Harlinghausen was forced into early retirement.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] The non-commissioned officers of *JaBoG 32* sent a letter to Strauß requesting that Barth should retain his command, without receiving any answer.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] Eventually, a proper investigation was conducted which found Barth to be innocent, a result unacceptable to Kammhuber, who initiated a second investigation that found the *Oberstleutnant* partly at fault.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] A third investigation followed, which again found Barth to be innocent.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] Oberstleutnant Barth then lodged an official complaint against Franz-Josef Strauß.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] Strauß, as minister of defence, ordered all witnesses in the case – Generals Kammhuber, Harlinghausen, Werner Panitzki and Werner Streib as well as Lieutenant Colonels Walter Krupinski and Walter Grasemann – not to speak, as they were all military personnel and therefore under his command.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] Nevertheless, his conduct in dismissing Barth was found to be at fault, and the latter had to be reinstated in his position.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] Strauß, however, ignored this decision until Hellmuth Heye, Ombudsman for the Military, forced him to accept it.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] Strauß himself was later forced to resign from his post as Minister of Defence, in the wake of the *Spiegel* scandal in 1962.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] Kammhuber retired from his post in the same year.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] Upon arrival at Tegel, the two planes were immediately hidden in hangars and journalists were prohibited from taking pictures of them.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] For years after, it was believed that the two planes had been repainted as aircraft of the United States Air Force and returned to West Germany by USAF pilots, or that they had been disassembled and transported back to the West in pieces.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] The arrival of two massive Douglas C-124 at Tegel from Frankfurt am Main also fuelled speculations that the two F-84s would be transported back in these aircraft.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] Another theory (which turned out to be true) held that the two aircraft were hidden by the French authorities at Tegel and, later, buried at the airfield, where they were accidentally rediscovered in the 1970s.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] In an exhibition at the *Luftwaffenmuseum Berlin-Gatow* in 2006, pictures of the two buried and then rediscovered Thunderstreaks at Tegel were shown, finally clearing up the question of what became of the two planes.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] The pilots of the two Thunderstreaks, Pfefferkorn and Eberl, were banned from flying and transferred to the ground crew at Lechfeld.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] The F-84F Thunderstreak, in service with the *Jagdbombergeschwader 32* since inception of the unit on 22 July 1958, was phased out of service on 13 July 1966, the *Geschwader* having accumulated over 80,000 flight hours with the planes.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] Winkler, who had been returning from a training exercise on board U.S.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] Navy aircraft carrier USS *Saratoga* in the Atlantic Ocean, had to carry out an emergency landing at Ahlhorn, 45 km southwest of Bremen.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] The aircraft was eventually written-off.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] Winkler himself died less than four years later in an F-104 Starfighter accident on 10 May 1966.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] On 28 January 1964, an unarmed T-39 Sabreliner aircraft of the United States Air Force (USAF) was shot down while on a training mission over Erfurt, East Germany, by a MiG-19 jet fighter of the Soviet Air Force.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] The occupants of the aircraft were Lieutenant Colonel Gerald K.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] Hannaford, Captain Donald Grant Millard, and Captain John F.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] All three died, becoming direct casualties of the Cold War in Europe.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] The Cold War developed between the Soviet bloc and the United States, Canada, and Western European nations.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] One of the most famous of these is the 1960 U-2 incident when the Soviets shot down a Lockheed U-2 spy plane piloted by Francis Gary Powers over the Soviet Union in May 1960.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] On 28 January 1964, an unarmed USAF North American T-39A Sabreliner twin engine jet trainer, *62-4448*, of the 7101st Air Base Wing, departed Wiesbaden Air Base, West Germany, at 14:10 hours on a routine three-hour training flight.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] On board the trainer were three men, Captain John F.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] Lorraine and students Lieutenant Colonel Gerald K.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] Lorraine was the qualified instructor, while Hannaford and Millard, both pilots with experience on other types, were being trained in order to qualify on the T-39.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] The flight proceeded uneventfully until, 47 minutes after takeoff, radar at two U.S. air defense stations noticed that the trainer was heading toward East Germany at 500 miles per hour (800 km/h).
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] Hoping to divert the T-39 back on course, each station began hailing the plane on USAF frequencies and a Soviet-monitored international distress band.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] Repeated calls to the T-39 went unanswered.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] It appeared that the T-39's radio systems malfunctioned and the crew were unable to respond.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] The T-39 crossed the border into East Germany.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] Within five minutes, two blips appeared near the American jet.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] For 11 minutes, radar blips indicated the three planes were moving eastward, then two blips suddenly veered west and the third blip disappeared.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] American personnel monitoring the T-39's flight could not determine what had happened, although it was later reported that residents in Vogelsberg, 50 miles (80 km) from the border, had heard machine-gun and cannon fire and had witnessed the plane crash.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] The incident is believed to have occurred at 15:14 hours.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] At 17:00 hours on 28 January the United States Military Liaison Mission (USMLM), in Berlin, received a warning to stand by for possible search and rescue of American airmen.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] By 18:00 hours, a search team left Berlin for the Erfurt area of East Germany.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] At 19:15 hours, the chief of the USMLM met with his Soviet counterpart to request help in finding the plane and rescuing survivors (in accordance with the Huebner–Malinin Agreement).
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] At 20:00 hours, a second search team left Berlin.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] About this same time, the first team arrived at the crash site, 20 kilometers (12 mi) north of Erfurt.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] The first team received a report from an East German civilian that a U.S. plane had crashed and burned, and that the crew was dead.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] Throughout the night, the American teams tried to approach the aircraft and were repeatedly sent away by the armed Soviet forces on site.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] These forces denied that any aircraft had crashed, and the two American search teams were detained briefly before being released at 14:00 hours on 29 January.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] By 29 January, the United States State Department charged that the Soviet Union shot down an unarmed plane and caused the needless deaths of three officers.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] Secretary of State Dean Rusk called the action a "shocking and senseless act." Through the Soviet press agency, Tass, Moscow claimed that the plane had intruded over East German territory and failed to react to signals, and then a warning shot.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] The Soviets said they were compelled to take the measure that brought down the U.S. plane.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] On 30 January, the Soviets agreed to allow US personnel access to the crash site.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] This occurred the following day and later the bodies of all three servicemen were returned to the United States through Andrews Air Force Base in Maryland.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] LeMay met the plane and participated in an honors ceremony.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] The aircraft wreckage was also recovered and was taken to Berlin, arriving there on 1 February 1964.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] Residents from the nearby town of Vogelsberg in Thuringia erected a memorial to the three downed pilots, in 1998, once the Iron Curtain had been lifted.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] The **1972 Olympic men's basketball final** was the last game of that year’s Olympic basketball tournament, and became one of the most controversial events in Olympic history.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] With the ending mired in controversy, during regulation play Team USA defeated the Soviet Union by one point, but the Soviet Union was awarded the victory after play was repeatedly extended.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] Both the U.S. and the Soviet Union won their first eight games of the tournament, with the U.S. team having its overall Olympic record at 63–0 when they advanced to the final against the USSR.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] The final three seconds of the game were played three times under questionable rule interpretations, leading to an ultimate victory by the Soviet team.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] The result of the game is disputed to this day, with widespread allegations of political corruption.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] The United States team had won the previous seven gold medals at the Olympics, and was among the contenders to win another in Munich at the 1972 Summer Olympics.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] The United States and Soviet Union sporting rivalry reached its peak during the Cold War.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] The U.S. men's team was considered a favorite in the run-up to the 1972 Games.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] Since the first Olympic basketball tournament at the 1936 Olympics in Berlin, the Americans had not lost a single game, winning seven consecutive gold medals in dominating fashion.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] Their record reached an unprecedented 63–0 before the final game.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] Since the 1952 tournament the Soviet team challenged the Americans, winning silver in 1952, 1956, 1960, 1964 and bronze in 1968.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] Outside of the Olympics, the Soviets had already defeated the U.S. team in FIBA World Championship play (at the 1959 world tournament and the 1963 world tournament).
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] However, the Americans never sent their best collegiate players to that tournament.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] The Olympics strictly prohibited any involvement of professional athletes at the time.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] The Soviet Union and other Eastern Bloc countries used that rule to their advantage, listing all their top players as soldiers or workers, which allowed them to breach the amateur rules.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] Western experts classified these athletes as professionals.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] On the other hand, leading American players were unable to play in the Olympics as they were officially professional and played in the NBA.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] That disadvantage had not prevented the Americans from winning the first seven Olympic basketball tournaments without a single defeat.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] The confrontation of the Soviet Union and United States on the basketball court was deeply connected to the confrontation on the political front.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] Many American viewers assumed the 1972 Games were openly anti-American.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] There were rumors that the Communist party had bribed the officials because they wanted the USSR to win 50 gold medals at these Olympics in commemoration of the 50th anniversary of the Soviet Union.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] The United States team was the youngest in history.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] American players usually participated in the Olympics once before turning pro, and the U.S. team always had new players every four years.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] The 1972 team did not have a clear leader.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] UCLA's Bill Walton, then a rising star, declined an invitation to participate.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] Some saw it as a political statement given Walton's opposition to the Vietnam War, but the most likely reason for his decision was his bad experience at the 1970 FIBA World Championship.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] They followed American basketball closely and they knew that no Walton was going to be a big deal." Nevertheless, the team was favored, featuring such players as Doug Collins and Tommy Burleson (the tallest player among all teams).
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] The young American team was confronted by a veteran Soviet team, featuring stars Sergei Belov, Modestas Paulauskas, and Alexander Belov.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] The players had played together for more than seven years.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] For Gennadi Volnov it was the fourth Olympic appearance.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] In 2004, Johnny Bach, an assistant on the 1972 American team, told ESPN: "Their team, it was reported, played almost 400 games together.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] The basketball gold medal was the last in contention.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] The Soviets were clearly ahead in the medal standings, but for political reasons they needed to win 50 golds (having 49 before the final match).
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] Both teams started out strong, winning their first games by an average of 37 points.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] However, the Americans experienced a slump winning their fourth game against Brazil by only seven points with a score of 61–54.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] However, they rebounded and defeated Egypt by 65 (96–31) and Japan by 66 (99–33).
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] Meanwhile, the Soviets had an easier time in their group, winning most of their games by more than 20.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] The only exceptions were against Italy (79–66) and Puerto Rico (100–87) when they won by 13.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] Their closest game was their last game when they played against Yugoslavia and won by seven (74–67).
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] Both teams were undefeated going into the semifinals when they faced the other group's runner-up (there was no quarterfinals at this point).
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] The United States made easy work of Italy, defeating them 68–38, while the Soviets struggled against Cuba, winning by only six (67–61).
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] This set up the gold medal match of the U.S. vs the USSR.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] The Soviets surprised the Americans early, led by Sergei Belov.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] The Soviets kept the Americans 4–8 points behind during the first half.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] In the second half the Soviets provoked Dwight Jones, the leading scorer of the U.S. team.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] On the 28th minute during a loose ball scuffle he was assailed by Mikheil Korkia and responded.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] After this, Ivan Dvorny was also disqualified for protesting from the bench.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] The Soviets benefited from the double ejection, as they deemed Korkia less significant for them than Jones was to the Americans.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] The next minute Alexander Belov violently injured Jim Brewer during the free-throw, and Brewer was unable to continue playing.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] With ten minutes left, the Soviets increased their lead to ten points.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] The Americans began to press, and led by Kevin Joyce were able to cut down Soviets' lead to one with thirty eight seconds left.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] With seven seconds to play, Doug Collins stole Alexander Belov's cross-court pass at half court and was fouled hard by Zurab Sakandelidze as he drove toward the basket, being knocked down into the basket stanchion.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] With three seconds remaining on the game clock, Collins was awarded two free throws and sank the first to tie the score at 49.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] Just as Collins lifted the ball to begin his shooting motion in attempting the second free throw, the horn from the scorer's table sounded, marking the beginning of a chain of events that left the game's final three seconds mired in controversy.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] Lead referee Renato Righetto turned away from the free throw attempt upon hearing the horn, but failed to stop play.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] Collins never broke his shooting motion and continued with his second free throw, scoring to put the U.S. ahead by a score of 50–49.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] Immediately following Collins' second free throw, with the ball then being a "live" ball under the rules at the time, Soviet assistant coach Sergei Bashkin charged out of the team's designated bench area to the scorer's table.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] He asserted that head coach Vladimir Kondrashin had called for a time-out, which should have been awarded prior to the second free throw, but that it had not been granted to them.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] Since a time-out could not legally be called *after* the second free throw, however, the Soviet players had to immediately inbound the live ball without a pre-planned play for the final three seconds.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] Alzhan Zharmukhamedov inbounded the ball to Sergei Belov, who began to dribble up the sideline, but the disturbance at the scorer's table led Righetto to stop play just as Belov approached mid-court.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] The game clock was stopped with one second remaining.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] When play was stopped, the Soviets pressed their argument about the time-out, with Kondrashin and Bashkin claiming that it had been called as soon as Collins was fouled.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] By the rules at that time, a time-out could be requested either by informing the scorer's table directly, or by pressing the button of an electronic signaling device, which in turn would illuminate a light bulb at the scorer's table to alert the officials there of the coach's desire for a time-out.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] According to Kondrashin, he requested his time-out by pressing the button.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] Also by the rules at the time, upon calling a time-out prior to free throws, the coach was allowed to choose to have it awarded either before the first free throw or between the two free throws; he said he had chosen to take it between the two free throws.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] The game's referees, however, were not informed of a Soviet time-out request prior to giving the ball to Collins for the second free throw.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] The unexplained horn that sounded as Collins was shooting the second free throw may have happened because the scorer's table had recognized the Soviet time-out request at the last moment and was attempting to stop the second free throw to award it.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] Renato William Jones, the secretary general of FIBA at the time, later asserted that the problem had indeed been a human error at the scorer's table which resulted in the time-out request being relayed too late to the on-court officials.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] Despite Kondrashin's and Jones' assurances, the Americans have expressed doubt that the time-out was really called.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] They have also argued that regardless of whether a time-out may have been missed, the ball became live upon Collins' second free throw, and as such, a technical foul should have been assessed against the Soviets because their coach left the designated bench area during live play.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] According to Righetto, after considering the Soviet arguments, the official decision was to *deny* the time-out.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] The protest later filed by the United States also mentioned that the game's official score sheet included no indication of a time-out being granted in the last three seconds.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] Collins has also confirmed that officially, the time-out was not awarded, which meant that Collins' second free throw counted and that neither team was to be allowed to substitute players when play resumed.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] Further indicators that no time-out was officially granted to the Soviets can be found in the existing television footage of the game, which includes shots of the scoreboard both before the incident and at the game's conclusion, indicating each time that Soviets had one time-out remaining.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] During the period between the game's interruption and resumption, the footage also does not include the sound of the scorer's table horn that typically would be used to signal both the start and the end of an officially charged time-out.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] However, even without being granted an official time-out, the minute-long delay to restore order on the court and determine how to proceed still gave the Soviet coaches time to confer with their players and devise a planned inbounds play.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] Furthermore, although Bashkin's actions had caused the game to be stopped with one second remaining on the clock, the officials decided neither to resume play from that point, nor to assess a technical foul against him for having interrupted the play.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] They instead wiped out the play altogether, ruling that the entire inbounds sequence would be replayed from the point immediately following the second free throw and that the game clock would thus be reset to three seconds.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] Jones, who had had a contentious relationship with American basketball officials for a number of years, came down from the stands to the court to contribute to the officials' ruling, and he insisted upon a complete replay of the final three seconds.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] According to Tenschert, Righetto had initially declared that play would resume with just one second remaining, only to be overruled by Jones.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] Jones later acknowledged that under the Olympic regulations, he had no authority to make rulings about a game in progress, though he maintained that resetting the clock was the correct course of action.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] The players were brought back into position for a second inbounds play.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] However, instead of Zharmukhamedov returning to throw the inbounds pass, Kondrashin managed to substitute Ivan Edeshko into the game in Zharmukhamedov's place, something that wasn't allowed as the time-out wasn't officially awarded.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] Kondrashin's plan was to have Edeshko attempt a length-of-the-court pass to center Alexander Belov near the American basket, confident that Belov could catch any pass thrown accurately to him there and feeling that Edeshko was the player most skilled in executing such a pass.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] The two players had successfully run much the same play for CSKA Moscow team the preceding year to claim the Soviet Championship.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] Under the Olympic rules, substitutions were not to have been allowed without the granting of the time-out, but the referees resumed the game, failing to notice this issue and also not noticing that clock operator Andre Chopard was still working on getting the game clock set to three seconds.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] The ball was given to Edeshko to start play, with the scoreboard clock actually showing 50 seconds remaining.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] Edeshko was defended at the end line by American center Tom McMillen.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] With his 6 ft 11 in (2.11 m) frame, McMillen aggressively challenged Edeshko's inbounds attempt, making it difficult for Edeshko to pass the ball into play.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] Edeshko ultimately made only a short pass to teammate Modestas Paulauskas standing in the Soviet backcourt.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] Paulauskas then immediately relayed a pass toward Belov at the other end of the court.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] But the horn sounded, with the pass barely out of Paulauskas's hand.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] The pass then missed its mark and was uneventfully tipped off the backboard.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] The players, the announcers of both television broadcasts, and the majority of the spectators in the arena all interpreted the sound of the horn, combined with the sight of a failed Soviet pass, as the end of the game.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] People flooded the court and the U.S. team began a joyful celebration of its apparent one-point victory.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] With Jones still involved in the process, the officials once again ordered the court to be cleared, the players to be brought back into position, the clock to be reset, and the final three seconds be replayed.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] The public speaker announced, "Please go out.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] There are another three seconds left." Furious over the decision to deny the U.S. victory and allow the Soviets yet a third inbounds play, the U.S. coaches briefly considered unilaterally declaring the game to be over by pulling their team off the floor.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] However, head coach Henry "Hank" Iba was concerned that such an action would leave the U.S. vulnerable to a Soviet appeal, which might lead to a ruling that the U.S. had forfeited the game.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] U.S. assistant coach John Bach reported that Jones threatened him directly with such a forfeiture should the U.S. team not return to the floor.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] On the third inbound try, McMillen was again assigned to use his height to challenge Edeshko's inbound pass.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] However, as official Artenik Arabadjian prepared to put the ball into play, he gestured to McMillen.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] McMillen responded by backing several feet away from Edeshko, which gave Edeshko a clear view and unobstructed path to throw a long pass down the court.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] McMillen later said that Arabadjian had instructed him to back away from Edeshko.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] McMillen said that despite the fact that there was no rule which would require him to do so, he decided to comply, fearing that if he did not, Arabadjian might assess a technical foul against him.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] For his part, Arabadjian has denied that his gesture was intended to instruct McMillen to back away from Edeshko.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] In any event, McMillen's repositioning left no American defender to challenge Edeshko's pass.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] Unlike the previous play, where he had been forced to make a short pass into the backcourt, Edeshko now had a clear line to throw the ball the length of the court toward Alexander Belov.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] Edeshko would later confirm that McMillen's backing away made it easy for him to throw the long pass downcourt.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] In the Soviet Union, Edeshko's throw would eventually come to be known as "the golden pass".
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] The images of the play broadcast on American television by the ABC network have led to the question of whether Edeshko might have stepped on the end line—meaning that he should have been called for a violation—as he made his pass.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] As Edeshko's full-court pass came down, Belov, Kevin Joyce and Jim Forbes all leapt for the ball near the basket.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] Belov caught the ball in the air, and as the three men landed, Joyce's momentum carried him out of bounds, while Forbes came down off-balance and fell to the floor beneath the basket.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] Belov then gathered himself and made an uncontested layup, scoring the winning points as the horn sounded for the last time.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] After jubilantly sprinting to the other end of the court, Belov was mobbed by his delirious teammates who dogpiled atop him in celebration.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] American coaches and players argued with the game officials for several minutes, but to no avail, as the Soviets were declared the victors.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] By some accounts, at the end of the game, Righetto refused to sign the official scoring sheet in an act of protest.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] Herb Mols, serving as the resident manager of the U.S. team, and U.S.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] Olympic Basketball Committee chairman MK Summers, filed a detailed protest, which was heard by FIBA's five-member jury of appeal.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] The protest asserted that allowing a third inbounds play with the clock reset to three seconds brought the total elapsed game time to 40 minutes and three seconds, in violation of FIBA rules which specified the length of a game to be 40 minutes.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] The jury ultimately voted down the protest and awarded the gold medals to the Soviet team.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] At the ensuing press conference, Mols engaged in an animated argument with the jury's chairman, Ferenc Hepp of Hungary, about the propriety of resetting the clock to three seconds.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] In announcing the verdict, Hepp steadfastly refused to provide the specifics of the vote count, acknowledging only that the decision was not unanimous.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] With three of the five jury members, including Hepp, being from Soviet-allied nations, this fueled speculation that the tally had been 3–2 and perhaps based more upon Cold War politics than upon the FIBA rulebook.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] Nonetheless, Hepp, the only one who had seen all five votes of the secret ballot, maintained his refusal to divulge the specific votes of any of the panel members, beyond later granting that his own vote was in favor of the Soviets.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] Despite this absence of confirmation from Hepp, it has become generally accepted and reported as fact that there indeed was a 3–2 vote that matched the political alliances of the time.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] Aside from potential political motivations, Mols suggested that panel members feared retribution from Jones were they to have deemed his decision regarding the game clock to be incorrect.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] In any event, the U.S. players did not accept the jury's verdict, voting unanimously to refuse their silver medals, and the team did not attend the medal ceremony.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] The silver medals are still kept in a vault in Lausanne, Switzerland.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] After the conclusion of the games, the United States Olympic Committee launched another appeal, this time to the executive committee of the International Olympic Committee (IOC).
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] It received the support of Righetto, who was quoted saying the Soviet victory was "completely irregular, and outsides the rules of the game of basketball".
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] Righetto criticized Jones's insistence that the clock be reset to three seconds, and offered that he felt it would have been more fair to have instead resumed play with only the one second on the clock that had been remaining when play was suspended.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] Righetto also asserted that the initial confusion was partially attributable to a language barrier, as he, a Brazilian, spoke Portuguese, but those working the scorer's table spoke only German.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] Also supporting the U.S. appeal was Chopard, who noted that in his 12 years of service as a timekeeper, Jones' order to put elapsed time back onto the clock was unprecedented.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] The appeal was unsuccessful, however, as in February 1973, the IOC ruled that matter fell under FIBA's jurisdiction.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] In the ensuing years, USA Basketball has periodically contacted the 1972 U.S. team members on behalf of the IOC to offer them the opportunity to change their stance and accept the silver medals, possibly being granted an official ceremony awarding them.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] In 1992, team member Ed Ratleff said that although he did not personally want the medal, his wife felt very strongly about his accepting it and being able to show it to their children.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] He said that his vote would be to accept the medal, but that he was casting his vote that way only in deference to her wishes.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] In a 2012 interview with Todd Jones of *The Columbus Dispatch*, Ratleff emphasized that the desire to accept the silver medal was his wife's, not his.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] Since divorced, he affirmed his intention never to accept it.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] The ten remaining team members each told the magazine that they would vote to refuse the acceptance of silver medals.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] With regard to awarding the medals, the IOC has insisted that for such an action, the entire team would need to consent unanimously.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] Kenny Davis reported that he had gone so far as to have a clause put into his will forbidding his wife, children or descendants from ever accepting the silver medal after his death.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] In 2012, Davis organized a reunion of the 12 team members—the first time they had all been together since 1972—and reported that after some discussion, the group was unanimous in its rejection of the silver medals.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] "In basketball, there's one winner," he said.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] "By the rules of that game, we won." The gathering included a group round-table interview of the players that was documented in the ESPN *30 for 30* short film *Silver Reunion*.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] The 2002 decision arose because a French judge had been unduly pressured by the Russian officials to inflate the scores of the Russian pair.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] The American appeal argued that Jones' unauthorized intervention in 1972 brought similar undue pressure upon the officiating crew of that game.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] According to McMillen, the IOC did not respond to his appeal.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] In the Soviet Union, the outcome of the game was heralded and the players celebrated as heroes, with comparatively little attention given to the controversy surrounding the team's victory.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] When asked about the subject, Soviet team members have indicated that they view their triumph as having been achieved legitimately.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] Edeshko and Sergei Belov, in particular, have been critical of the Americans for refusing to accept having lost, with Edeshko saying that he regrets that others may feel the Soviets' gold medals were undeserved, but that he harbors no such doubts himself.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] From his perspective as coach, Kondrashin acknowledged that the controversy did somewhat diminish his enjoyment of the triumph.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] However, he still cited the victory as the greatest accomplishment of his basketball career.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] The game and its controversies are presented from a Russian point of view as part of the 2017 Russian sport drama film *Going Vertical* (Russian: Движение вверх, romanized: *Dvizhenie vverkh*).
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1972-olympic-men-s-basketball-final] The game is also featured in the ESPN documentaries *Silver Reunion* (2013; part of *30 for 30*), and Episode 2 of *Basketball: A Love Story* (2018).
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1973-united-states-soviet-union-wheat-deal] The **1973 United States–Soviet Union wheat deal** was a series of large Soviet purchases of American wheat and other grains.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1973-united-states-soviet-union-wheat-deal] It was negotiated with private U.S. exporters during July and August 1972, with deliveries scheduled through August 1973.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1973-united-states-soviet-union-wheat-deal] The Soviets contracted for about 440 million bushels of wheat (roughly US$700 million) along with additional grain purchases, tightening world supplies and contributing to sharp rises in grain and food prices in 1972–1973.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1973-united-states-soviet-union-wheat-deal] The sales were facilitated by a July 1972 U.S. government credit agreement making up to US$750 million available over three years for Soviet purchases of U.S. grains, and by export-subsidy mechanisms that supported contracting at fixed export “target” prices despite rising domestic market prices.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1973-united-states-soviet-union-wheat-deal] In the United States the episode became widely known as the **“Great Grain Robbery”** (or “Great Russian Grain Robbery”), and Congress subsequently mandated an export sales reporting system in 1973 to improve transparency around large agricultural export transactions.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1973-united-states-soviet-union-wheat-deal] Soviet grain output was highly variable and, by the early 1970s, the USSR was increasingly supplementing domestic supplies with imports.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1973-united-states-soviet-union-wheat-deal] In 1972 the USSR suffered heavy winterkill of winter grains following severe frosts with little or no snow cover, followed by a drought and unusually hot conditions over much of the European USSR during the growing season; in some areas east of the Urals, wet conditions also complicated harvesting.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1973-united-states-soviet-union-wheat-deal] The USSR's reported gross output of grain and pulses in 1972 was about 168 million tonnes (*bunker weight*), down from 181.2 million tonnes in 1971.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1973-united-states-soviet-union-wheat-deal] As crop prospects deteriorated, the Soviet government purchased roughly 28 million tonnes of grain abroad for delivery in 1972–73, including about 18 million tonnes from the United States.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1973-united-states-soviet-union-wheat-deal] Contemporary analyses of the 1972–73 price spike treated the Soviet shortfall as a major factor tightening world grain markets.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1973-united-states-soviet-union-wheat-deal] Later meteorological analyses comparing major events in the region noted that the summer of 1972 produced heat extremes in parts of Eastern Europe comparable to those seen in 2010, although 2010 set new records in many station series.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1973-united-states-soviet-union-wheat-deal] The main negotiations for the deal took place on June 20, 1972, at The Madison hotel in Washington, D.C., with two Soviet teams, one led by foreign trade minister Nikolai Patolichev and the second led by Nicolai Belousov.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1973-united-states-soviet-union-wheat-deal] On the American side were multiple representatives of American grain businesses and officials representing the U.S. government.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1973-united-states-soviet-union-wheat-deal] This included Michel Fribourg, the CEO of grain trading firm ContiGroup Companies (formerly Continental Grain), and Carroll Brunthaver, the U.S.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1973-united-states-soviet-union-wheat-deal] Under Secretary of Agriculture for Farm and Foreign Agricultural Services.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1973-united-states-soviet-union-wheat-deal] In early July 1972, the U.S. government negotiated an arrangement that allowed the Soviets to buy up to $750 million of American grain on credit, over a three-year timespan.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1973-united-states-soviet-union-wheat-deal] However, the Soviets quickly exceeded their credit limit, spending the $750 million in only one month.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1973-united-states-soviet-union-wheat-deal] By September 1972, the Soviets are thought to have spent up to US$1 billion on grain from companies in the United States, and more from other countries such as France, Canada, and Australia.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1973-united-states-soviet-union-wheat-deal] The U.S. government spent $300 million subsidizing the grain purchases, still unaware that the Soviets had suffered massive crop shortfalls in 1971 and 1972.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1973-united-states-soviet-union-wheat-deal] One reason the government did not realize the impact the deal would have is that many officials, such as Earl Butz, were convinced that the Soviets were purchasing the grain only to feed their livestock.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1973-united-states-soviet-union-wheat-deal] By not realizing that global wheat stocks were low, and discounting reports of Soviet crop failure, the United States inadvertently contributed to domestic food prices rising, using public funds to do so.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1973-united-states-soviet-union-wheat-deal] Weeks after the grain deal was announced, the Earth-observing satellite Landsat 1 achieved orbit.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1973-united-states-soviet-union-wheat-deal] If the satellite had launched a few months earlier, the deal may have been reconsidered or never have happened at all, because American negotiators could have realized the scale of Soviet crop failures.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1973-united-states-soviet-union-wheat-deal] The event helped lead the U.S. government to seek more information about global agricultural output via infrared satellite intelligence.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1973-united-states-soviet-union-wheat-deal] After the deal, many Americans were concerned about businesses having advantages in similar situations due to their early access to information.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1973-united-states-soviet-union-wheat-deal] In a ten-month span in 1973, global food prices rose by at least 30 percent and some sources claim up to 50 percent.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1973-united-states-soviet-union-wheat-deal] In some British markets there was a reported 87 percent increase on the price of an 800 grams (28 oz) loaf of bread.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1973-united-states-soviet-union-wheat-deal] Global wheat stocks decreased exponentially; Australia was hit the hardest with a 93 percent decrease by 1974 from 1971.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1973-united-states-soviet-union-wheat-deal] Not all nations were equally hit; some, such as Canada, benefited from the deal.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1973-united-states-soviet-union-wheat-deal] Canadian farmers had sold their wheat to the Canadian Wheat Board, which were able to pool stocks and sell as a collective.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1973-united-states-soviet-union-wheat-deal] Contemporary U.S. media referred to the event as "The Russian Wheat Deal" or "The Soviet Wheat Deal".
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/1973-united-states-soviet-union-wheat-deal] The term *Great Grain Robbery* is a pun referring to the 1963 Great Train Robbery and it is generally accepted that it was coined by Senator Henry M.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/american-expeditionary-force-north-russia] The **American Expeditionary Force, North Russia** (**AEF in North Russia**, also known as the **Polar Bear Expedition**) was a contingent of about 5,000 United States Army troops that landed in Arkhangelsk, Russia as part of the Allied intervention in the Russian Civil War.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/american-expeditionary-force-north-russia] It fought the Red Army in the surrounding region during the period of September 1918 through to July 1919.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/american-expeditionary-force-north-russia] President Woodrow Wilson sent the Polar Bear Expedition to Russia in response to requests from the governments of Great Britain and France to join the Allied Intervention in North Russia (also known as the North Russia Campaign).
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/american-expeditionary-force-north-russia] Army's 85th Division left their training camp at Camp Custer, Michigan for the Western Front in France and Belgium.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/american-expeditionary-force-north-russia] Three days later, President Wilson agreed to limited participation by American troops in the Allied Intervention with the stipulation that they would only be used for guarding the stockpiled war material.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/american-expeditionary-force-north-russia] Pershing received the directive from President Wilson, he changed the orders for the 339th Infantry Regiment, along with the First Battalion of the 310th Engineers plus a few other ancillary units from the 85th Division.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/american-expeditionary-force-north-russia] Instead of heading for France, these units were trained and re-outfitted in England with Russian guns and then sent to North Russia.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/american-expeditionary-force-north-russia] They arrived in Arkhangelsk on September 4, 1918, coming under British command.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/american-expeditionary-force-north-russia] See American Expeditionary Force, Siberia for information on the 7,950 American soldiers and officers sent to Vladivostok, Russia at the same time.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/american-expeditionary-force-north-russia] When the British commanders of the Allied Intervention arrived in Arkhangelsk on August 2, 1918, they discovered that the Allied war material had already been moved up the Dvina River by the retreating Bolshevik forces.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/american-expeditionary-force-north-russia] Therefore, when the American troops arrived one month later, they were immediately used in offensive operations to aid in the rescue of the Czechoslovak Legion.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/american-expeditionary-force-north-russia] The British commanders sent the First Battalion of the 339th Infantry up the Dvina River and the Third Battalion of the 339th up the Vologda Railroad where they engaged and pushed back the Bolshevik forces for the next six weeks.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/american-expeditionary-force-north-russia] However, these two fronts each became hundreds of miles (kilometers) long and were extremely narrow and difficult to supply, maintain, and protect.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/american-expeditionary-force-north-russia] By the end of October 1918, they were no longer able to maintain the offensive and acknowledging their fragile situation and the rapid onset of winter, the Allies began to adopt a defensive posture.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/american-expeditionary-force-north-russia] The Allied commanders also soon realized they would be unable to raise an effective local force of anti-Bolshevik soldiers.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/american-expeditionary-force-north-russia] Thus they gave up the goal of linking up with the Czechoslovak Legion and settled in to hold their gains over the coming winter.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/american-expeditionary-force-north-russia] During that winter, the Bolshevik army went on the offensive, especially along the Vaga River portion of the Dvina River Front, where they inflicted some casualties and caused the Allies to retreat a considerable distance.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/american-expeditionary-force-north-russia] Following the Allied Armistice with Germany on November 11, 1918, family members and friends of soldiers in the AEF began writing letters to newspapers and circulating petitions to their representatives in the U.S.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/american-expeditionary-force-north-russia] Congress, asking for the immediate return of the force from North Russia.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/american-expeditionary-force-north-russia] In turn, the newspapers editorialized for their withdrawal and their congressmen raised the issue in Washington, D.C.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/american-expeditionary-force-north-russia] Meanwhile, aware of not only the change in their mission, but also of the Armistice on the Western Front and the fact that the port of Arkhangelsk was now frozen and closed to shipping, the morale of the American soldiers plummeted.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/american-expeditionary-force-north-russia] They asked their officers why they were fighting Bolshevik soldiers in Russia and did not receive a clear answer, other than that they had to fight to survive and avoid the Bolshevik army pushing them into the Arctic Ocean.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/american-expeditionary-force-north-russia] Early in 1919, instances of rumored and actual mutinies in the Allied ranks became frequent.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/american-expeditionary-force-north-russia] In March 1919, four American soldiers in Company B of the 339th Infantry drew up a petition protesting their continued presence in Russia and were threatened with court-martial proceedings.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/american-expeditionary-force-north-russia] In early June, the bulk of the AEF in North Russia sailed for Brest, France and then for New York City and home—which for two-thirds of them was in the state of Michigan.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/american-expeditionary-force-north-russia] During the withdrawal, the men of the AEF in North Russia decided to call themselves "Polar Bears" and were authorized to wear the Polar Bear insignia on their left sleeve.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/american-expeditionary-force-north-russia] On July 15, 1919, it was reported by the *Alaska Daily Empire* that forty-six officers and 1,495 men of the Polar Bear Expedition, were the first American troops to return home from service in Northern Russia, arrived in Hoboken, New Jersey aboard the Von Steuben.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/american-expeditionary-force-north-russia] The AEF in North Russia officially disbanded on August 5, 1919.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/american-expeditionary-force-north-russia] During their time in North Russia, the American forces suffered more than 210 casualties, including at least 110 deaths from battle, about 30 missing in action, and 70 deaths from disease, 90% of which were caused by the Spanish flu.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/american-expeditionary-force-north-russia] An October 1919 report gives the casualties as 553: 109 killed in battle; 35 died of wounds; 81 from disease; 19 from accidents/other causes; 305 wounded and 4 POWS (released).
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/american-expeditionary-force-north-russia] Several years after the American troops were withdrawn from Russia, President Warren G.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/american-expeditionary-force-north-russia] Harding called the expedition a mistake and blamed the previous administration.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/american-expeditionary-force-north-russia] By that time, 112 sets of remains had already been transferred to the United States.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/american-expeditionary-force-north-russia] By 1929, additional research found that 226 fallen Polar Bears had originally been buried in North Russia, with a total of approximately 130 sets of U.S. soldier remains then estimated to still be buried in North Russia.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/american-expeditionary-force-north-russia] Hampered by the lack of diplomatic recognition between the United States and the Soviet Union, it took many years before they finally received permission.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/american-expeditionary-force-north-russia] An expedition under the auspices of the Veterans of Foreign Wars (VFW) was successful in organizing and conducting a recovery mission in the autumn of 1929 that found, identified and brought out the remains of 86 U.S. soldiers.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/american-expeditionary-force-north-russia] The remains of 14 AEF in North Russia soldiers were shipped by the Soviet Union to the U.S. in 1934, which reduced the number of U.S. soldiers still buried in North Russia to about 30.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/american-expeditionary-force-north-russia] The remains of 56 AEF soldiers were eventually re-buried in plots surrounding the Polar Bear Memorial by sculptor Leon Hermant in White Chapel Memorial Cemetery, Troy, Michigan in a ceremony on May 30, 1930.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/american-expeditionary-force-north-russia] Harold Gunnes, who was born in 1899, died on March 11, 2003.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-north-russia/american-expeditionary-force-north-russia] Gunnes was believed to have been the last living American to have fought in the Allied Intervention near the port of Arkhangelsk on the White Sea.
